        section.bg-light
            .container.px-4
                .row.gx-4.justify-content-center
                    .col-lg-8
                        h2 What are the benefits of knowledge management?
                        p.lead
                            | Below, we've outlined the advantages of knowledge management and how it contributes to the success of your customers.
                        h2 Organised knowledge-base
                        p.lead
                            | According to a 2022 Gartner study on customer service leaders' priorities, 74% emphasised the importance of enhancing content and knowledge delivery for both customers and employees in their support strategy. The efficient organisation and presentation of collective knowledge from a centralised repository streamlines scattered information silos within organisations
                        p.lead
                            | Plus, it helps in establishing a single source of truth. Such a system ensures clear organisation of critical information and effective search capabilities that enable visitors to easily find the information they require when they need it.
                        h2 Updated knowledge-base
                        p.lead
                            | A knowledge management system helps in identifying outdated articles, allowing for a straightforward process of updating them with current information. This advantage contrasts with the potential disorganisation of a file folder filled with documents
                        p.lead
                            | A KMS ensures the orderly organisation of valuable information, preventing the risk of misleading customers with outdated data and potentially losing their business, emphasising the importance of promptly addressing ageing information.                     
                        h2 Self-service-centric
                        p.lead
                            | A significant 78% of US leaders are increasing investments in self-service, incorporating customer self-help portals and AI-powered chatbots to empower them in finding solutions independently.
                        p.lead
                            | Self-service, where customers assist themselves through documentation, stands out as the most cost-effective customer support approach. This can be achieved through an extensive knowledge base, AI chatbots, or community forums.                       
                        p.lead
                            | These self-help alternatives leverage a centralised and updated knowledge management system to retrieve relevant solution articles and FAQs, effectively deflecting tickets away from the customer support team.                               
                        h2 Share and Reuse
                        p.lead
                            | Are your customer support agents investing substantial time in crafting detailed support emails? Utilising a KMS allows you to harness that knowledge by transforming these support emails into knowledge base articles. 
                        p.lead
                            | In essence, a knowledge management system democratises valuable information, encouraging knowledge sharing accessible to everyone in the company. Consequently, customers gain prompt access to helpful information at their fingertips. 
                        h2 Customer retention
                        p.lead
                            | Approximately 39% of customers favour self-service options over engaging with human agents. Fortunately, knowledge management software offers 24/7 support, allowing customers to quickly locate information without waiting in a phone queue.
                        p.lead
                            | As customers effortlessly find their own answers, you can anticipate a rise in customer satisfaction (CSAT) scores. Consistently enhancing the delivery of information through an online help centre contributes to reducing churn, enhancing customer loyalty, and improving customer retention.

                        h2 Better customer support
                        p.lead
                            | Communication through email or phone has its limitations. Knowledge management systems offer the ability to consolidate various types of media, ensuring comprehensive assistance.
                        p.lead
                            | Customers have diverse learning preferences, whether through text, videos, or images. By incorporating all these options into your help centre, you ensure that all customers receive the assistance they need, catering to their preferred method of consuming online material.

